  "10.35": (
    caption: [Problems of refraction and how they are corrected. In a normal eye (a), parallel rays of light are brought to a focus on the retina by refraction in the cornea and lens. If the eye is too long, as in myopia (b), the focus is in front of the retina. This can be corrected by a concave lens. If the eye is too short, as in hyperopia (c), the focus is behind the retina. This is corrected by a convex lens. In astigmatism (d), light refraction is uneven because of irregularities in the shape of the cor...],
